CodonProfiler: analyze codon usage patterns across transcriptome

Kai Hu1, Haibo Liu1, Richard Gregory1 and Lihua Julie Zhu1

1Molecular, Cell and Cancer Biology, University of Massachusetts Medical School, Worcester, MA, USA

15 August 2025

Abstract

Instructions on using CodonProfiler for codon usage analysis.

Package

CodonProfiler 0.1.0

1 Introduction

Codon usage bias, or simply codon bias, refers to the non-random preference for synonymous codons encoding the same amino acid. Genomic codon bias reflects the inherent codon composition encoded in the genome, shaped over evolutionary time by mutations and natural selection. In contrast, transcriptomic codon bias captures the dynamic usage of codons in expressed mRNAs, influenced by factors such as tRNA availability, translation efficiency, and mRNA stability.

While several tools and databases exist for calculating and visualizing various codon usage metrics, integrating codon usage information into biological discovery remains challenging, especially when working with transcriptome-level data or mutation-rich samples, such as those derived from cancer studies. The CodonProfiler package addresses these challenges by providing a comprehensive and flexible toolkit that streamlines common codon usage analyses. It supports calculation of diverse codon usage metrics, with optional TPM weighting; incorporates mutation-aware analyses using variant data; and enables pathway-level assessments of codon usage differences across biological conditions or disease states.

The core features and a typical workflow using CodonProfiler for codon usage analysis are summarized in the diagram below. Detailed examples demonstrating the packages capabilities are presented in the A Typical Workflow section.

Figure 1: A typical workflow using CodonProfiler

2 Installation

library(devtools)

install_github("hukai916/CodonProfiler")

3 Quick start

A CodonStats object serves as the core data container for codon usage analysis in this package. We can create one using the CodonStats() constructor by specifying a genome assembly name, currently supported genomes include mm10 (mouse) and hg38 (human). The constructor initializes a CodonStats object with a tx_raw slot that holds all raw transcript retrieved from the EnsDb database for the chosen genome.

library(CodonProfiler)
## 
csm <- CodonStats("mm10")
## Creating `CodonStats` object ...
##   Note: 267 transcript(s) are excluded as their seqnames do not appear in the genome.
## Creating `CodonStats` object: done!
head(tx_raw(csm))
## # A tibble: 6  7
##   GENEID             GENENAME TXID               TXBIOTYPE    SEQ   WIDTH STRAND
##   <chr>              <chr>    <chr>              <chr>        <chr> <int> <chr> 
## 1 ENSMUSG00000000001 Gnai3    ENSMUST00000000001 protein_cod ATGG  1065 -     
## 2 ENSMUSG00000000003 Pbsn     ENSMUST00000000003 protein_cod ATGA   525 -     
## 3 ENSMUSG00000020875 Hoxb9    ENSMUST00000000010 protein_cod ATGT   753 +     
## 4 ENSMUSG00000000028 Cdc45    ENSMUST00000000028 protein_cod ATGT  1701 -     
## 5 ENSMUSG00000048583 Igf2     ENSMUST00000000033 protein_cod ATGG   543 -     
## 6 ENSMUSG00000000049 Apoh     ENSMUST00000000049 protein_cod ATGG  1038 +

We can apply filters using set_tx_filter() to retain only valid transcripts. By default, this keeps protein-coding transcripts that have a valid start codon, a valid stop codon, and a CDS length divisible by three. The applied filters are stored in the tx_filter slot. Next, we populate the tx_filtered slot with the transcripts that pass these filters by calling set_tx_filtered(). These filtered transcripts are then used for downstream analyses.

# Add desired CDS filters
csm <- set_tx_filter(csm,
                     value = c("protein_coding", 
                               "start_codon", 
                               "stop_codon", 
                               "three_multiplier"))

# Show added filters
tx_filter(csm)
## [1] "protein_coding"   "start_codon"      "stop_codon"       "three_multiplier"
# Apply filters
csm <- set_tx_filtered(csm)
head(tx_filtered(csm))
## # A tibble: 6  7
##   GENEID             GENENAME TXID               TXBIOTYPE    SEQ   WIDTH STRAND
##   <chr>              <chr>    <chr>              <chr>        <chr> <int> <chr> 
## 1 ENSMUSG00000000001 Gnai3    ENSMUST00000000001 protein_cod ATGG  1065 -     
## 2 ENSMUSG00000000003 Pbsn     ENSMUST00000000003 protein_cod ATGA   525 -     
## 3 ENSMUSG00000020875 Hoxb9    ENSMUST00000000010 protein_cod ATGT   753 +     
## 4 ENSMUSG00000000028 Cdc45    ENSMUST00000000028 protein_cod ATGT  1701 -     
## 5 ENSMUSG00000048583 Igf2     ENSMUST00000000033 protein_cod ATGG   543 -     
## 6 ENSMUSG00000000049 Apoh     ENSMUST00000000049 protein_cod ATGG  1038 +

Next, we compute a variety of codon usage metrics from the filtered transcripts using set_codon_usage(). The results are organized as a list of tibbles stored in the codon_usage slot, with each tibble representing a distinct set of codon usage metrics.

csm <- set_codon_usage(csm)

names(codon_usage(csm))
##  [1] "use_tx"                         "use_tpm_weighted"              
##  [3] "global"                         "global_normalized"             
##  [5] "global_rscu"                    "per_tx"                        
##  [7] "per_tx_normalized_by_tx_length" "per_tx_normalized_by_global"   
##  [9] "per_tx_milc"                    "per_tx_enc"                    
## [11] "per_tx_enc_prime"               "per_tx_rscu"                   
## [13] "per_tx_cai"
head(codon_usage(csm)$global)
##    AAA    AAC    AAG    AAT    ACA    ACC 
## 481957 416698 707147 330957 336970 380236

4 A typical workflow

The following examples demonstrate a typical workflow using CodonProfiler to analyze codon usage, with a focus on uncovering biological insights from codon usage patterns. This workflow involves four main steps:

  • Initialize a CodonStats object
  • Prepare coding sequence (CDS)
  • Compute codon usage
  • Compute pathway-level codon usage

4.1 Step1: Initialize a CodonStats object

Creating a CodonStats object is as simple as passing the desired genome name to the CodonStats() constructor. The resulting object, csm, contains a slot named tx_raw that holds all raw transcripts retrieved from EnsDb.

csm <- CodonStats("mm10")
## Creating `CodonStats` object ...
##   Note: 267 transcript(s) are excluded as their seqnames do not appear in the genome.
## Creating `CodonStats` object: done!
head(tx_raw(csm))
## # A tibble: 6  7
##   GENEID             GENENAME TXID               TXBIOTYPE    SEQ   WIDTH STRAND
##   <chr>              <chr>    <chr>              <chr>        <chr> <int> <chr> 
## 1 ENSMUSG00000000001 Gnai3    ENSMUST00000000001 protein_cod ATGG  1065 -     
## 2 ENSMUSG00000000003 Pbsn     ENSMUST00000000003 protein_cod ATGA   525 -     
## 3 ENSMUSG00000020875 Hoxb9    ENSMUST00000000010 protein_cod ATGT   753 +     
## 4 ENSMUSG00000000028 Cdc45    ENSMUST00000000028 protein_cod ATGT  1701 -     
## 5 ENSMUSG00000048583 Igf2     ENSMUST00000000033 protein_cod ATGG   543 -     
## 6 ENSMUSG00000000049 Apoh     ENSMUST00000000049 protein_cod ATGG  1038 +

4.2 Step2: Prepare coding sequence (CDS)

Before calculating codon usage, the coding sequences must be prepared by filtering out transcripts that are unsuitable for codon analysis. The following filters are currently supported:

  • protein_coding: The transcript must be protein-coding.
  • start_codon: The transcript must begin with a codon from start_codon(csm), which defaults to c("ATG").
  • end_codon: The transcript must end with a codon from stop_codon(csm), which defaults to c("TAA", "TAG", "TGA").
  • three_multiplier: The CDS length must be divisible by 3.
  • longest_tx: If multiple transcripts exist for the same gene, only the longest one is retained.
  • selected_tx: Only transcripts in the selected_tx vector are retained.

To apply these filters, use set_tx_filter() to add the desired ones to the csm object. By default, set_tx_filter adds the filters protein_coding, start_codon, end_codon, three_multiplier, which retain only protein-coding transcripts with valid start and stop codons, and a CDS length divisible by three. After setting the filters, run set_tx_filtered() to populate the tx_filtered slot with the filtered transcripts.

# Add desired filters
csm <- set_tx_filter(csm)

# Apply filters
csm <- set_tx_filtered(csm)
head(tx_filtered(csm))
## # A tibble: 6  7
##   GENEID             GENENAME TXID               TXBIOTYPE    SEQ   WIDTH STRAND
##   <chr>              <chr>    <chr>              <chr>        <chr> <int> <chr> 
## 1 ENSMUSG00000000001 Gnai3    ENSMUST00000000001 protein_cod ATGG  1065 -     
## 2 ENSMUSG00000000003 Pbsn     ENSMUST00000000003 protein_cod ATGA   525 -     
## 3 ENSMUSG00000020875 Hoxb9    ENSMUST00000000010 protein_cod ATGT   753 +     
## 4 ENSMUSG00000000028 Cdc45    ENSMUST00000000028 protein_cod ATGT  1701 -     
## 5 ENSMUSG00000048583 Igf2     ENSMUST00000000033 protein_cod ATGG   543 -     
## 6 ENSMUSG00000000049 Apoh     ENSMUST00000000049 protein_cod ATGG  1038 +

We can check, for each transcript, how many filters it passes using set_tx_stat(), which stores the results in the tx_stat slot, and visualize the results using plot_tx_stat(). When applying filters, instead of removing incomplete transcripts, e.g.those missing start codon or stop codon, we can attempt to rescue them by setting set_tx_filtered(rescue_incomplete_cds = TRUE), type ?set_tx_filtered for more details.

library(dplyr)
csm <- set_tx_stat(csm)

tx_stat(csm)$tx_raw %>% 
  select(c(TXID, tx_filter(csm))) %>% 
  head()
## # A tibble: 6  5
##   TXID               start_codon stop_codon three_multiplier protein_coding
##   <chr>              <lgl>       <lgl>      <lgl>            <lgl>         
## 1 ENSMUST00000000001 TRUE        TRUE       TRUE             TRUE          
## 2 ENSMUST00000000003 TRUE        TRUE       TRUE             TRUE          
## 3 ENSMUST00000000010 TRUE        TRUE       TRUE             TRUE          
## 4 ENSMUST00000000028 TRUE        TRUE       TRUE             TRUE          
## 5 ENSMUST00000000033 TRUE        TRUE       TRUE             TRUE          
## 6 ENSMUST00000000049 TRUE        TRUE       TRUE             TRUE
plot_tx_stat(csm)

The Venn diagram shows that about 70% of transcript are retained after filtering. Addtionally, the selected_tx filter enables users to specify particular transcripts for analysis. This is useful when focusing on specific genes or pathways of interest. We can apply this filter using the following command. Note that the selected_tx filter can be combined with other filters.

selected_tx <- c("ENSMUST00000000001", 
                  "ENSMUST00000000003", 
                  "ENSMUST00000000010", 
                  "ENSMUST00000000028", 
                  "ENSMUST00000000033", 
                  "ENSMUST00000000049")
csm_demo <- set_tx_filter(csm, 
                          value = "selected_tx", 
                          selected_tx = selected_tx)
csm_demo <- set_tx_filtered(csm_demo)
dim(tx_filtered(csm_demo))

4.3 Step3: Calculate codon usage

After obtaining the filtered transcripts, we can calculate codon usage using set_codon_usage(). The results are stored as a list of tibbles in the codon_usage slot, each tibble containing distinct codon usage metrics. By default, the following metrics are computed:

  • global: Raw codon counts for each codon across the entire transcriptome.
  • global_normalized: Normalized global, where codon counts are divided by the total codon count. This serves as a background codon usage profile useful for cross-genome comparisons.
  • global_rscu: The Relative Synonymous Codon Usage (RSCU) values calculated from global.
  • per_tx: Raw codon counts for each codon within every transcript.
  • per_tx_normalized_by_tx_length: per_tx counts normalized by transcript length (i.e., codon counts divided by transcript length).
  • per_tx_normalized_by_global: Further normalization of per_tx_normalized_by_tx_length by dividing against global_normalized for each codon.
  • per_tx_milc: Measure Independent of Length and Composition (MILC) score for each transcript, which quantifies codon usage bias while accounting for sequence length and composition.
  • per_tx_enc: Effective Number of Codons (ENC) score for each transcript, which measures the degree of codon usage bias.
  • per_tx_enc_prime: The ENCprime score for each transcript, an improved version of ENC that better handles extreme codon usage bias.
  • per_tx_rscu: RSCU values calculated at each transcript level.

If you set include_CAI = TRUE, the following metric is also calculated:

  • per_tx_cai: The Codon Adaptation Index (CAI) score for each transcript, which quantifies codon usage bias relative to that observed in highly expressed gene sets.
csm <- set_codon_usage(csm)

# View the raw global codon counts
codon_usage(csm)$global %>% head()
##    AAA    AAC    AAG    AAT    ACA    ACC 
## 481957 416698 707147 330957 336970 380236
# View the raw per-transcript codon counts
codon_usage(csm)$per_tx %>% head()

4.3.1 Add TPM weight

To capture dynamic codon usage patterns at the transcriptome level, TPM weighting can be applied when calculating codon usage metrics. By definition, certain per-transcript metrics, such as enc, enc_prime, and milc, are unaffected by TPM weighting at the transcript level. In contrast, metrics like global raw count, global normalized count, global_rscu, per_tx will change when TPM weighting is applied. See ?set_codon_usage for more details.

The example below uses a TPM file derived from an RNA-seq dataset of mouse ESCs (GSE174492). Instructions for preparing TPM files are available via ?example_tpm.

# Read in WT1 TPM file
wt1_tpm <- system.file("extdata", "tpm/wt1_tpm.sf", package = "CodonProfiler")
csm_wt1_tpm <- set_tpm(csm, tpm = wt1_tpm)
head(tpm(csm_wt1_tpm))
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   TXID                 TPM
##   <chr>              <dbl>
## 1 ENSMUST00000177564     0
## 2 ENSMUST00000196221     0
## 3 ENSMUST00000178537     0
## 4 ENSMUST00000178862     0
## 5 ENSMUST00000179520     0
## 6 ENSMUST00000179883     0
# Calculate codon usage with TPM weighting
csm_wt1_tpm <- set_codon_usage(csm_wt1_tpm, use_tpm_weighted = TRUE)
## Note: number of transcripts with TPM > 0: 19479/37927.
# View the raw global codon counts before and after adding TPM weight
head(codon_usage(csm)$global)
##    AAA    AAC    AAG    AAT    ACA    ACC 
## 481957 416698 707147 330957 336970 380236
head(codon_usage(csm_wt1_tpm)$global)
##     AAA     AAC     AAG     AAT     ACA     ACC 
## 2404824 1619475 4072309 1201971 1256898 1453406

4.3.2 Inject mutations

Mutations can significantly alter codon usage patterns. For mutation-rich samples, we can introduce single nucleotide variants (SNVs) directly into the coding sequences using set_tx_mutated(). This function generates a new slot, tx_mutated, which stores the mutation-injected transcripts. We can then calculate codon usage on these mutated transcripts by calling set_codon_usage(use_tx = "tx_mutated").

The following example uses a 1% subset of a mutation file from TCGA-BRCA (https://portal.gdc.cancer.gov/projects/TCGA-BRCA). Details on how this file was prepared can be found in the documentation by running ?example_maf. Since the mutation data is based on the hg38 genome, the CodonStats object must be initialized with genome = "hg38".

# Create a new `CodonStats` object with "hg38"`
csh <- CodonStats("hg38")
## Creating `CodonStats` object ...
##   Note: 8576 transcript(s) are excluded as their seqnames do not appear in the genome.
## Creating `CodonStats` object: done!
csh <- set_tx_filter(csh)
csh <- set_tx_filtered(csh)

# Read in mutation file
maf_file <- system.file("extdata", "maf/brca_maf_subset.maf", package = "CodonProfiler")

# Inject mutations
csh <- set_tx_mutated(csh, mutation_file = maf_file)
## Loading exon info ...
## Loading exon info: done!
## Parsing mutation file ...
## Parsing mutation file: done!
## Injecting mutations to transcripts ...
##  2134 mutations are found in 1962 out of 54231 transcripts.
## Injecting mutations into transcripts: done!
# Calculate codon usage
csh <- set_codon_usage(csh, use_tx = "tx_filtered")
csh_mutated <- set_codon_usage(csh, use_tx = "tx_mutated")

# View the raw global codon counts before and after mutation injection
head(codon_usage(csh)$global)
##    AAA    AAC    AAG    AAT    ACA    ACC 
## 733382 532347 916808 497369 439191 515259
head(codon_usage(csh_mutated)$global)
##    AAA    AAC    AAG    AAT    ACA    ACC 
## 733451 532379 916817 497387 439234 515293

By default, set_tx_mutated() injects mutations into transcripts from tx_filtered and stores results in tx_mutated slot. To inject mutations into transcripts from tx_raw, use set_tx_mutated(use_tx = "tx_raw"). After injection, codon usage can be calculated from the mutated transcripts with set_codon_usage(use_tx = "tx_mutated").

If both TPM-weighting and mutation injection are applied, codon usage can be calculated with the combined effects using set_codon_usage(use_tx = "tx_mutated", use_tpm_weighted = TRUE).

4.3.3 Visualize codon usage patterns

CodonProfiler includes a suite of plotting functions for exploring and visualizing codon usage patterns.

4.3.3.1 Plot1: Global codon usage

A scatter plot can be used to visualize global codon usage patterns across the entire transcriptome.

plot_global_codon_usage(csm, 
                        x_axis = "count", 
                        y_axis = "rscu")

We can compare global codon usage patterns between two genomes.

plot_global_codon_usage_corr(csm, csh, metric = "rscu")

4.3.3.2 Plot2: Top transcripts

  • per-transcript metrics

For per-transcript metrics like enc, cai, and milc, bar plots can be used to visualize the transcripts with top values.

# Plot transcripts with the top 10 lowest ENC
plot_metric_top(csm, 
                metric = "enc", 
                top = 10)

In addition, we can visualize the distribution of these metric values across all transcript to gain a broader overview of codon usage bias.

plot_metric_dist(csm, metric = "enc")

  • per-codon metrics

For codon-level metrics like raw counts and rscu, we can visualize, for selected codons, the top transcripts most enriched with those codons.

plot_metric_per_codon(csm, 
                      codon = "AGA", 
                      top_n = 10, 
                      by = "rscu")
## $AGA

# If multiple codons are specified, a list of plots will be returned
p_list <- plot_metric_per_codon(csm, 
                                codon = c("AAA", "TTT"), 
                                top_n = 10,
                                by = "rscu")
p_list$AAA

Plots can be saved by specifying the outdir argument.

4.3.3.3 Plot3: Codon enrichment

For codon-level metrics, we can also use heatmap to visualize codon enrichment patterns across transcripts.

plot_codon_enrichment(csm, metric = "rscu")

4.4 Step4: Compute pathway-level codon usage

Similar to transcript-level codon usage, metrics such as enc, enc_prime, cai, milc, and rscu can be computed at the pathway level by aggregating all transcripts with each pathway.

To perform pathway-level calculations, pathway information must first be added using set_pathway_info(). For demonstration, only five random pathways are added. By default, pathway_ids = NULL, and all available pathway information for the genome is retrieved from the KEGGREST database. The fetched pathway data is stored in the pathway_info slot.

# Add pathway information for 5 random pathways
csm <- set_pathway_info(csm, 
                        pathway_ids = c("mmu04110", "mmu04151", 
                        "mmu04010", "mmu04660", "mmu00010"))
##  Retrieving pathway info ...
##   Pathway(s) to retrieve: 5
##  Retrieving pathway info: done!
# View the added pathway information
pathway_info(csm) %>% head()
## # A tibble: 6  4
##   GENEID             ENTREZ_ID PATHWAY_ID PATHWAY_NAME

4.4.1 Visualize pathway-level codon usage patterns

Similar to transcript-level codon usage patterns, we can visualize the codon usage patterns at the pathway level.

4.4.1.1 Plot1: Top pathways

  • per-transcript metrics

As in Step 3, per-transcript metrics such as enc, cai, and milc can be visualized using bar plots to highlight pathways with top metric values by setting level = "pathway".

# Plot transcripts with the top five lowest ENC
csm <- set_codon_usage_pathway(csm, metric = "enc")
plot_metric_top(csm, 
                metric = "enc", 
                level = "pathway",
                top = 5)

Also, we can visualize the distribution of these metric values across all pathways to gain an overview of codon usage variation at the pathway level.

plot_metric_dist(csm, metric = "enc", level = "pathway")

  • per-codon metrics

For codon-level metrics like raw counts and rscu, we can visualize, for selected codons, the top pathways enriched with those codons.

plot_metric_per_codon(csm, 
                      codon = "AGA", 
                      top_n = 5, 
                      level = "pathway",
                      by = "rscu")
## $AGA

4.4.1.2 Plot2: Codon enrichment

As in Step 3, codon-level metrics including raw counts, normalized counts, and rscu, can be visualized using heatmaps to reveal codon enrichment patterns at the pathway level.

plot_codon_enrichment(csm, 
                      metric = "rscu", 
                      level = "pathway", 
                      label_row = TRUE,
                      downsample = 1)

4.4.1.3 Plot3: Differentially used codons (DUCs)

  • Scenario 1: Pathway-level DUCs against background

To identify differentially used codons (DUCs) at the pathway level, we can compare the pathway-level codon usage (e.g.rscu) against the background codon usage, e.g., the global codon usage. DUCs identified this way reflect the codon preferences of a specific pathway relative to the genomic average. P-values can be calculated using either Fishers exact test or the Chi-squared test. The results are stored in the pathway_duc slot.

csm <- set_pathway_duc(csm)
##  Calculating pathway DUC ...
##  Calculating pathway DUC: done!
# View the pathway-level DUCs
pathway_duc(csm) %>% head()
## # A tibble: 6  14
##   PATHWAY_ID PATHWAY_NAME        CODON RSCU_PATHWAY RSCU_GLOBAL FC_RSCU   PVALUE
##   <chr>      <chr>               <chr>        <dbl>       <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 mmu00010   Glycolysis / Gluco TTT          0.832       0.903   0.921 1.59e- 3
## 2 mmu00010   Glycolysis / Gluco TTC          1.17        1.10    1.06  1.59e- 3
## 3 mmu00010   Glycolysis / Gluco TTA          0.197       0.424   0.464 8.61e-30
## 4 mmu00010   Glycolysis / Gluco TTG          0.703       0.806   0.873 4.45e- 4
## 5 mmu00010   Glycolysis / Gluco CTT          0.616       0.808   0.763 2.27e-11
## 6 mmu00010   Glycolysis / Gluco CTC          1.27        1.16    1.10  1.09e- 3
## #  7 more variables: PADJ <dbl>, COUNT_PATHWAY <dbl>, COUNT_GLOBAL <dbl>,
## #   AA <chr>, COUNT_SYN_PATHWAY <dbl>, COUNT_SYN_GLOBAL <dbl>, GENOME <chr>

To visualize pathway-level DUCs, we can use plot_pathway_duc(). By default, this function generates a heatmap showing the rscu fold change of each codon relative to the global background for each pathway.

plot_pathway_duc(csm)
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs for 5 pathways.
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs: done!

We can also generate volcano plots for each pathway by setting type = "volcano".

p_list <- plot_pathway_duc(csm, type = "volcano")
## Plotting volcano plot for pathway DUCs for 5 pathways.
## Plotting volcano plot for pathway DUCs: done!
p_list[[1]]

By setting the outdir parameter, plots will be saved to the specified directory. By setting the outcsv parameter, intermediate results will be saved as a CSV file. Additionally, use the pathway_id argument to generate plots for selected pathways only.

plot_pathway_duc(csm, 
                 type = "volcano", 
                 pathway_id = "mmu04660")
## Plotting volcano plot for pathway DUCs for 1 pathways.
## Plotting volcano plot for pathway DUCs: done!

  • Scenario 2: Pathway-level DUCs between two conditions

Instead of comparing against the background codon usage, we can compare two CodonStats objects to identify DUCs at the pathway level. This approach enables detection of pathways enriched for specific codons in one condition relative to the other. For more details, see Use Case 1 below.

5 Use Case 1

In this example, we aim to identify pathways enriched with specific codons in one condition compared to another. We leverage the same TPM files as in Step 3, which are prepared from a RNA-seq dataset of mouse ESCs (GSE174492). Specifically, we will compare the WT1 condition against the KO1 condition to find differentially used codons (DUCs) at the pathway level.

# Add pathway information
  # Here we only add 5 random pathways for demonstration
pathway_ids = c("mmu04110", "mmu04151", "mmu04010", 
                "mmu04660", "mmu00010")
csm <- set_pathway_info(csm, pathway_ids = pathway_ids)
##  Retrieving pathway info ...
##   Pathway(s) to retrieve: 5
##  Retrieving pathway info: done!
# Add TPM information 
wt1_tpm <- system.file("extdata", "tpm/wt1_tpm.sf", package = "CodonProfiler")
ko1_tpm <- system.file("extdata", "tpm/ko1_tpm.sf", package = "CodonProfiler")
csm_wt1_tpm <- set_tpm(csm, tpm = wt1_tpm)
csm_ko1_tpm <- set_tpm(csm, tpm = ko1_tpm)

# Calculate pathway-level codon usage
  # Without TPM weighting
csm <- set_codon_usage(csm, use_tpm_weighted = FALSE) 
csm <- set_codon_usage_pathway(csm, metric = "rscu")

  # With TPM weighting
csm_wt1_tpm <- set_codon_usage(csm_wt1_tpm, use_tpm_weighted = TRUE)
## Note: number of transcripts with TPM > 0: 19479/37927.
csm_wt1_tpm <- set_codon_usage_pathway(csm_wt1_tpm, metric = "rscu")
csm_ko1_tpm <- set_codon_usage(csm_ko1_tpm, use_tpm_weighted = TRUE)
## Note: number of transcripts with TPM > 0: 18995/37927.
csm_ko1_tpm <- set_codon_usage_pathway(csm_ko1_tpm, metric = "rscu")

Now, for each of the csm, csm_wt1_tpm, and csm_ko1_tpm objects, pathway-level DUCs can be calculated against their respective global backgrounds and visualized separately.

csm <- set_pathway_duc(csm)
##  Calculating pathway DUC ...
##  Calculating pathway DUC: done!
csm_wt1_tpm <- set_pathway_duc(csm_wt1_tpm)
##  Calculating pathway DUC ...
##  Calculating pathway DUC: done!
csm_ko1_tpm <- set_pathway_duc(csm_ko1_tpm)
##  Calculating pathway DUC ...
##  Calculating pathway DUC: done!
plot_pathway_duc(csm, 
                 cluster_rows = FALSE, 
                 cluster_cols = FALSE)
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs for 5 pathways.
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs: done!

plot_pathway_duc(csm_wt1_tpm, 
                 cluster_rows = FALSE, 
                 cluster_cols = FALSE)
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs for 5 pathways.
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs: done!

plot_pathway_duc(csm_ko1_tpm, 
                 cluster_rows = FALSE, 
                 cluster_cols = FALSE)
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs for 5 pathways.
## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs: done!

It is clear that TPM-weighting significantly influences the pathway-level DUC results. The heatmap patterns for WT1 and KO1 against their respective global backgrounds appear similar. We can further compare WT1 directly to KO1 to identify pathway-level DUCs using the find_pathway_duc() function.

Unlike set_pathway_duc(), which calculates DUCs relative to the global background, find_pathway_duc() compares two CodonStats objects at the pathway level to identify DUCs. The fold change is calculated as the ratio of rscu values from the first CodonStats object divided by those from the second. The results are stored in a PathwayDUC object, which can be inspected using the pathway_duc() function.

pathway_duc <- find_pathway_duc(csm_ko1_tpm, csm_wt1_tpm)
## Found 5 pathways that are present in both x and y.
## Finding pathway DUCs...
## Finding pathway DUCs: done!
pathway_duc(pathway_duc) %>% head()

The DUCs can also be visualized with plot_pathway_duc().

plot_pathway_duc(pathway_duc,
                 type = "heatmap",
                 fc = 1.05,
                 padj = 0.05,

                 cluster_cols = FALSE,

## Plotting heatmap for pathway DUCs for 5 pathways.

It can be observed that there are three significant DUCs for the pathway mmu00010 and mmu04010 using padj = 0.05 and fc = 1.05. These DUCs can be visualized with volcano plots by setting type = "volcano".

plot_pathway_duc(pathway_duc,
                 type = "volcano",
                 pathway_id = "mmu00010",
                 fc = 1.05,
                 padj = 0.05)
## Plotting volcano plot for pathway DUCs for 1 pathways.
## Plotting volcano plot for pathway DUCs: done!

The above plots show that the codons CGT (Arg) and TTA (Leu) are significantly less favored in the KO1 condition compared to the WT1 condition within the mmu00010 pathway.
